{{About|the Mauritanian sprint athlete|other people with this name|Fatou Dieng (disambiguation){{!}}Fatou Dieng}}

'''Fatou Ndaga Dieng''' (born 14 September 1983) is a former [[Mauritania]]n sprint athlete, and is now a member of the Mauritania National Olympic and Sports Committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=NOC Mauritania|url=http://www.africaolympic.net/en/noc-mauritania-another-term-for-mohamed-mahmoud-ould-mah/|website=africaolympic.net|publisher=ANOCA|accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref>

In 2000 Dieng became the first female to compete for her country at the [[Summer Olympics]] when she went to the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] held in [[Sydney]], she entered the [[Athletics at the 2000 Summer Olympics – Women's 100 metres|100 metres]] and ran a in a time of 13.69 seconds, she finished 9th in her heat, Heat 7 which was ran on 22 September 2000, so didn't qualify for the next round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/di/fatou-dieng-1.html|title=Fatou Dieng Bio, Stats, and Results|website=Olympics at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-14}}</ref> She set a Mauritanian national record for the 100m at 13.29 seconds which she ran at the [[Jeux de la Francophonie]] in [[Ottawa]], [[Canada]] on 20 July 2001. She ran faster the next day, achieving a time of 11.87 seconds which still stands as the Mauritanian national record.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} She was entered into the senior 100m women's sprint event at the 2011 [[All-Africa Games]] in [[Maputo]], [[Mozambique]] but no result was recorded.<ref name = webcaa>{{cite web | url = http://www.webcaa.org/save/pdf/All_Africa_GamesFinalResults_15_Sep2011.pdf |title = All Africa Games 2011 Official results | accessdate = 2016-11-20 | publisher = webcaa.org}}</ref>

