{{Infobox venue | stadium_name = LaHaye Ice Center | nickname = | image = | location = [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], United States | broke_ground = 2005 | opened = 2006 | closed = | demolished = | owner = Liberty University | operator = | surface = 200' x 85' (hockey) | construction_cost= | architect = | former_names = | tenants =[[Liberty Flames]] men's and women's hockey | seating_capacity = 4,000 (hockey) }}
The '''LaHaye Ice Center''' is a 4,000-seat ice [[arena]] located in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]] on the campus of [[Liberty University]]. The ice arena is also the home to the [[Liberty Flames]] men's and women's [[college ice hockey|ice hockey]] teams that currently compete in the [[American Collegiate Hockey Association]] as independent teams in the [[American Collegiate Hockey Association|ACHA Division I]].<ref name="luministries1">{{cite web|url=http://www.luministries.com/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=6038 |accessdate=July 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309222114/http://www.libertyonlineministries.com/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=6038|title=Ice Center upgrades announced as LU men’s hockey team gears up for season opener |publisher=Liberty University |archivedate=March 9, 2012 }}</ref> In addition to LU's varsity teams, Liberty JV team, [[Virginia Military Institute]], and [[Lynchburg College]] teams at the [[American Collegiate Hockey Association|ACHA Division II]] level playing in the [[Blue Ridge Hockey Conference]] also use the arena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vmi.edu/show.aspx?tid=22373&id=25957 |title=Virginia Military Institute - Ice Hockey |publisher=Vmi.edu |date=2015-01-16 |accessdate=2015-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lynchburg.edu/x8409.xml |accessdate=July 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100607184810/http://www.lynchburg.edu/x8409.xml|title=Hornets welcomed to Division 3 Club Hockey |publisher=Lynchburg College |archivedate=June 7, 2010 }}</ref> And for LU's [[synchronized skating]] team.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.liberty.edu/libertyjournal/index.cfm?PID=15758&section=8&artid=712 |title=Liberty Journal &#124; Articles &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2009-04-01 |accessdate=2015-04-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229164229/http://www.liberty.edu/libertyjournal/index.cfm?PID=15758&section=8&artid=712 |archivedate=2012-02-29 |df= }}</ref> The ice arena is also used for various recreational uses by students and local public for [[ice skating]], [[figure skating]], [[ice hockey]], and [[broomball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimatelu.com/index.cfm?PID=17486|title=Facilities|publisher=Liberty University |accessdate=July 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090818200623/http://www.ultimatelu.com/index.cfm?PID=17486 |archivedate=August 18, 2009 }}</ref>
The arena is named after [[Tim LaHaye]], who gave $4.5 million to Liberty University to build a new student center and School of Prophecy, which opened in January 2002. He also serves as its president. LaHaye also provided the funds for the LaHaye Ice Center on the campus of Liberty University, which opened in January 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biographyministries.com/tim-lahaye-ministries.html|title=TIM LAHAYE MINISTRIES |website= Biographyministries.com|accessdate=July 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317100631/http://www.biographyministries.com/tim-lahaye-ministries.html |archivedate=March 17, 2010 }}</ref>
==Facilities== The {{convert|89000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} ice arena includes an [[NHL]] regulation-sized ice sheet and has a [[seating capacity]] of 4,000 spectators, a media press box, a president's seating area, concession stand, pro shop with skate rental. The arena also houses offices for ice sports coaches and personnel and locker rooms.<ref name="luministries1"/> The Ice Center received renovations in the summer of 2008 when a Chancellor’s suite and two business suites were installed on one side of the rink. Improvements were also made to the rink’s upper level/balcony, with a new conference room, space for LU’s hockey coaches, a players’ lounge and a meeting area for media. The renovations also included a locker room for public use and a permanent locker for the Liberty women’s hockey team.<ref name="luministries1"/> The arena was completely renovated again in 2015, expanding capacity by more than 1,000 and adding to the building's concession offerings and locker room space. A new four-sided videoboard was also added in the renovation.<ref>https://www.newsadvance.com/news/local/liberty-university-celebrates-re-opening-of-ice-center/article_c4e32ba5-1305-5a39-bb01-11facb6c7845.html</ref>
The first goal scored in the brand new LaHaye Ice Center was January 13, 2006 by Flames senior forward Scott LaPeer, giving Liberty a 1-0 lead over George Mason University in a game the Flames would win. That season, Liberty hockey's first in its new, on-campus arena, the Flames advanced to the ACHA National Championship game, eventually losing in overtime, 8-7, to Oakland University (Michigan).
