{{Infobox cricket ground | ground = Mitcham Cricket Green | image = Cricket on The Cricket Green, Mitcham. - geograph.org.uk - 19915.jpg | caption = Cricket match on Mitcham Cricket Green | location = [[Mitcham, London|Mitcham]], [[London Borough of Merton|Merton]] (previously [[Surrey]]) | home club = [[Mitcham Cricket Club]] | county club = [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey CCC Second XI]] | established = 1685 | last used = }}
'''Mitcham Cricket Green''' is a [[List of Test cricket grounds|cricket ground]] in [[Mitcham]], south [[London]] (historically in [[Surrey]]). It is the home of [[Mitcham Cricket Club]] and is reportedly the oldest cricket ground still in use, having been used for cricket since 1685.<ref name="Shaw">{{cite news | first=Phil | last=Shaw | pages=12 | title=Cricket: After 400 years, history is made next to the A323 | date=July 13, 2003 | publisher=[[The Independent]] | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/after-400-years-history--is-made-next-to-the-a323-648174.html | accessdate=2009-06-11| quote=Mitcham Green has been in continual use as a cricket venue for 317 years}} ''Note'': the roads next to the Cricket Green are the A217 and the A239, not the A323.</ref>
==History== In the 19th century, the [[Australia national cricket team|Australian cricket team]] would stay at ''The Cricketers'' [[pub]] which overlooks the green and practise on the green whilst on tour. The pub also held the changing rooms for the club during the late 18th century, with the scorer having a position on the balcony of the inn. The present pavilion was built in 1904 and is rare in being one of only a few cricket pavilions to be separated from the ground by a road, (the [[A239 road|A239]]).<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.merton.gov.uk/leisure/history-heritage/heritage-sites/mitcham_cricket_ground.htm | title =Mitcham Cricket Ground | accessdate =2007-02-06| date =18 October 2006 | work =Heritage Sites | publisher =[[London Borough of Merton]]}}</ref>
[[Surrey County Cricket Club]] first used the ground in 1949 for a match in the [[Minor Counties Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/90/90416.html |title=Surrey 2nd XI v Essex 2nd XI |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref> Surrey continued to use the ground for 2nd XI matches until 1973. Its first usage in the [[Second XI Championship]] was for a match in 1959.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/23/23641.html |title=Surrey 2nd XI v Gloucestershire 2nd XI |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref> Surrey has never used Mitcham for a [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match.
The most notable match of recent times was the [[Golden Jubilee]] Challenge Match, a match held between Mitcham and [[Hambledon Club]], two of the oldest clubs in the country, in honour of the [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II]]. [[Ian Botham]] made a guest appearance with the [[2002 Commonwealth Games#Queen's Jubilee Baton Relay|Queen's Jubilee Baton]]. The match was a two innings affair.<ref name="Shaw"/>
==Local government== The Cricket Green also lends its name to the nearby area, and is a [[Conservation area]] and [[Local government in the United Kingdom|council]] [[Ward (politics)|ward]].<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.merton.gov.uk/council/councillors.htm?view=ward&ward_id=21 | title =Councillors | accessdate =2007-02-06 | date =29 January 2007 | work =London Borough of Merton Website | publisher =[[London Borough of Merton]] }}</ref>
