{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Mitchells and Butlers' Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Birmingham]], [[Warwickshire]] | establishment = 1888 <small>(first recorded match)</small> | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year1 = 1931-1939 & 1957-1961 | club1 = [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] | date = 28 August | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/322.html Ground profile }}
'''Mitchells and Butlers' Ground''' was a [[cricket]] ground in [[Birmingham]], [[Warwickshire]]. The ground, near the [[Mitchells & Butlers Brewery|Mitchells & Butlers brewery]], was owned by [[Mitchells & Butlers]], which had its headquarters in Birmingham. The first recorded match on the ground was in 1888, when Mitchells played Warwickshire Club and Ground.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/322_misc.html Other matches played on Mitchells and Butlers' Ground]</ref> The first [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match came in 1931 when [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] played [[Kent County Cricket Club|Kent]]. From 1931 to 1939, the ground hosted 9 first-class matches. First-class cricket returned to the ground in 1957, with Warwickshire play 4 further first-class matches at the ground. The following season the last of which was between Warwickshire and [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/322_f.html First-Class Matches played on Mitchells and Butlers' Ground]</ref>
Additionally, the ground has played host to a number of matches involving the Warwickshire Second XI between 1949 and 1992.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/322_minc.html Minor Counties Championship Matches played on Mitchells and Butlers' Ground]</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/322_sec.html Second XI Championship Matches played on Mitchells and Butlers' Ground]</ref> The ground has also hosted a number of [[ICC Trophy]] matches, the first of which came in the [[1979 ICC Trophy]] between [[Denmark national cricket team|Denmark]] and [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]]. From 1979 to 1986, the ground hosted 4 ICC Trophy matches, the last of which saw Denmark play the [[Netherlands national cricket team|Netherlands]] in the [[1986 ICC Trophy]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/322_icct.html ICC Trophy Matches played on Mitchells and Butlers' Ground]</ref>
The final county match on the ground to date came in 1993 when the Warwickshire Second XI played the Marylebone Cricket Club Young Cricketers. Located just off Portland Road, today the ground is used as a [[association football|football]] venue and the home of Portland Pavilion Social Club.<ref>[http://www.theportlandpavilion.co.uk/aboutus.html Portland Pavilion Social Club] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527071359/http://www.theportlandpavilion.co.uk/aboutus.html |date=2009-05-27 }}</ref>
In late 2013, it was announced that [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club]] were in advanced talks to take control of the ground, to be used as a home for its Second XI and Youth Teams. In early November of the same year, Warwickshire's Chief Executive [[Colin Povey]] announced that the ground would be up and running for the 2015 season, with a new, smaller, pavilion, to replace that which was already at the site. It is possible that [[First Class Cricket|First-Class]] games will be played at the ground on occasion in the future, if Warwickshire's home [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground|Edgbaston]] is out of use, for an extended period, such as was the case for the [[Champions Trophy 2013|2013 Champions Trophy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/cricket/cricket-warwickshire-set-satellite-ground-6270989.html|title = Warwickshire set satellite ground|date = |accessdate = 30 March 2015|website = Birmingham Mail|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>
